        <!-- Page header -->
        <div class="docs-page-header">
            <span class="docs-badge">Documentation</span>
            <h1 class="docs-title">How UniCore Works</h1>
            <p class="docs-subtitle">
                UniCore connects people who need compute power with people who have hardware to spare —
                through a secure relay that keeps both sides private.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- What is UniCore -->
        <section id="what-is-unicore" class="docs-section">
            <h2>What is UniCore?</h2>
            <p>
                UniCore is a peer-to-peer distributed computing marketplace. Instead of paying
                a cloud provider like AWS or GCP for a virtual machine, you rent compute time
                directly from other people's idle hardware — at a fraction of the cost.
            </p>
            <p>
                If you have a spare PC, you can list it on UniCore and earn money whenever
                someone uses it. If you need a Linux VM for a build job, a dev environment,
                or a quick experiment, you can spin one up in seconds from your browser —
                no account setup, no port forwarding, no exposed IP addresses.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-cyan">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">The core insight</p>
                <p>
                    Most personal computers sit idle more than 90% of the time. UniCore lets
                    that idle capacity do useful work for someone else, and pays the owner for it.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <section id="architecture" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Architecture</h2>
            <p>
                UniCore has two separate communication paths: <strong>Firestore</strong> handles
                all coordination (VM requests, status updates, pause/resume signals), and an
                <strong>FRP relay on GCP</strong> carries the actual SSH traffic. Neither the
                consumer nor the provider ever exposes a public IP address.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-arch-diagram">
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-cyan">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">Consumer</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">Browser / SSH.NET</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">&harr;</div>
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-purple">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">GCP FRP Relay</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">Ports 2222–2300</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">&harr;</div>
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-green">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">Docker Container</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">sshd + frpc</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p style="text-align:center; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: -0.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
                SSH path &nbsp;·&nbsp; All coordination (VM requests, pause/resume, status) flows through Firestore
            </p>

            <div class="docs-steps">
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-green">1</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Provider comes online</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The provider installs the desktop app and authenticates with Firebase.
                            Their hardware specs are detected automatically and written to the
                            shared database. Their machine appears as available in the marketplace.
                            No inbound firewall rules are needed.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-cyan">2</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Consumer requests a VM</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The consumer visits the web app, selects CPU cores, RAM, disk size,
                            and a base image, then clicks "Launch VM." A matchmaking algorithm
                            selects the best available provider by consistency score and resource
                            availability. A VM record is created in Firestore with status
                            "Provisioning."
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-purple">3</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Container starts, FRP tunnel opens</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The provider app's Firestore listener detects the new VM record and
                            calls Docker to create a container. Inside the container, an FRP
                            client opens an outbound tunnel to the GCP relay, registering an SSH
                            port in the 2222–2300 range. A background service polls the relay
                            until the SSH banner is readable, then marks the VM "Running."
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-cyan">4</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Consumer gets a terminal</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The web app opens an in-browser terminal (WebShell). SSH.NET connects
                            to <code>relay-ip:relay-port</code>, which the FRP server tunnels
                            into the container's SSH daemon. The consumer has a full Linux shell.
                            The provider's real IP is never disclosed.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Getting a VM -->
        <section id="get-a-vm" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Getting a VM</h2>
            <p>
                Consumers access UniCore entirely through a browser — nothing to install.
            </p>

            <ol class="docs-ol">
                <li>Open the UniCore web app and sign in with your account.</li>
                <li>On your dashboard, click <strong>Create VM</strong> and choose CPU cores, RAM, disk size, and a base image.</li>
                <li>UniCore's matchmaking selects the best available provider for you automatically.</li>
                <li>Wait while the container starts and the FRP tunnel is established (typically under 30 seconds).</li>
                <li>Click the <strong>Terminal</strong> button on your VM card. A shell opens directly in your browser.</li>
                <li>When you're done, click <strong>Stop VM</strong>. Your files are backed up to cloud storage automatically.</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-green">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">No SSH client required</p>
                <p>
                    The terminal runs directly in your browser via a web-based SSH client (WebShell).
                    You don't need PuTTY, OpenSSH, or any other tool. You can also pause a VM
                    to stop billing without losing your session state.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Terminal Access -->
        <section id="terminal-access" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Terminal Access</h2>
            <p>
                Every VM provisioned through UniCore comes with:
            </p>
            <ul class="docs-ul">
                <li>A configurable base image (Ubuntu and other Linux images supported)</li>
                <li>Full <code>sudo</code> access inside the container</li>
                <li>Outbound internet access (for installing packages, cloning repos, etc.)</li>
                <li>Automatic volume backups to Google Cloud Storage every 5 minutes</li>
                <li>Container snapshots to GCP Artifact Registry every 2 hours (preserves installed packages)</li>
                <li>Isolated filesystem — your data is not visible to the provider</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                You can <strong>pause</strong> a VM at any time to freeze billing without losing your environment.
                If a provider goes offline unexpectedly, your most recent volume backup is preserved
                and can be restored on a different provider via live migration.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Becoming a Provider -->
        <section id="become-a-provider" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Becoming a Provider</h2>
            <p>
                Anyone with a spare Windows or Linux machine can become a provider. The minimum
                requirements are modest — most gaming PCs, home servers, and old workstations
                qualify.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-specs-grid">
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Minimum RAM</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">4 GB</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Minimum CPU</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">2 cores</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">OS</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">Win 10+ / Ubuntu 20.04+</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Required Software</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">Docker Desktop</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <ol class="docs-ol">
                <li>Download the UniCore Provider app for your platform.</li>
                <li>Install Docker Desktop if you don't already have it.</li>
                <li>Sign in with your UniCore account and complete provider onboarding.</li>
                <li>Set your resource limits — how much RAM and CPU to allocate for consumer VMs.</li>
                <li>Your hardware specs are detected automatically. Your machine is now listed in the marketplace.</li>
            </ol>

            <p>
                You can go offline any time by closing the provider app — it marks your node
                as offline in the marketplace automatically on shutdown. Consumer VMs that were
                running are backed up to cloud storage before the connection drops.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Earning & Payouts -->
        <section id="earning" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Earning &amp; Payouts</h2>
            <p>
                Providers are paid per hour of active consumer usage. Billing is prorated to
                the minute — consumers are never charged for idle time after their session ends.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-green">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">Consistency score</p>
                <p>
                    UniCore tracks provider uptime with a <strong>consistency score</strong> (0–100).
                    Every 10 seconds, a background heartbeat service probes each of your active VMs
                    via the FRP relay. Being reliably reachable improves your score and ranks you
                    higher in matchmaking, resulting in more VM assignments and more revenue.
                    Going offline unexpectedly reduces it.
                </p>
            </div>

            <p>
                Payouts are processed on a rolling basis. Minimum payout threshold and payment
                methods are configured in your provider dashboard.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Security Model -->
        <section id="security" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Security Model</h2>

            <div class="docs-security-grid">
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Provider IP never exposed</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        The FRP client inside each container connects <em>outbound</em> to the
                        GCP relay on port 7000. Consumers only ever see the relay's IP.
                        A provider's home or office IP is never transmitted to or visible by consumers.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Docker isolation</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        Each consumer session runs inside a Docker container. Consumers cannot
                        access the provider's host filesystem, processes, or network interfaces
                        outside the container.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Firebase JWT auth</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        All API calls are authenticated with short-lived Firebase JWTs. Tokens
                        are verified server-side on every request. Sessions expire and require
                        re-authentication.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">GCP-backed relay</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        The SSH relay is an FRP server running on a GCP Compute Engine VM.
                        FRP relay credentials (server address and auth token) are stored in
                        GCP Secret Manager and loaded at runtime — never committed to source control.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="docs-section">
            <h2>FAQ</h2>

            <div class="docs-faq">
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Do consumers need to create an account?</summary>
                    <p>
                        Yes. A UniCore account is required to use the platform. Sign-up is free
                        and takes under a minute using email and password via Firebase Authentication.
                        Email verification is required before accessing the dashboard.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>What happens if the provider goes offline mid-session?</summary>
                    <p>
                        The relay detects the disconnection within seconds and the consumer's
                        terminal will display a connection-lost message. However, your work is
                        not lost: UniCore automatically backs up your home directory to Google
                        Cloud Storage every 5 minutes and takes a full container snapshot
                        every 2 hours. You can migrate your VM to a different provider and
                        resume where you left off. The heartbeat service also tracks this event
                        and reduces the provider's consistency score accordingly.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Can I run GPU workloads?</summary>
                    <p>
                        GPU passthrough is on the roadmap. Currently, only CPU-based workloads
                        are supported. Providers with CUDA-capable GPUs will be able to opt in
                        to GPU listings in a future release.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Is my data private from the provider?</summary>
                    <p>
                        All consumer workloads run inside Docker containers. Providers cannot
                        inspect the container filesystem or processes during a live session.
                        However, as with any shared compute environment, you should avoid
                        processing highly sensitive credentials or data you wouldn't trust
                        to a third-party VPS.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>How is pricing set?</summary>
                    <p>
                        Providers set their own hourly rate. UniCore takes a small platform fee.
                        The consumer-facing price shown in the marketplace is the all-in price
                        including the platform fee.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>What ports are available in a consumer VM?</summary>
                    <p>
                        VMs have full outbound internet access. You can also expose a web service
                        running inside your VM (default port 8080) via a public HTTPS subdomain
                        at <code>&lt;vmId&gt;.services.cbu-unicore.com</code>. This is tunneled
                        through the same FRP relay and served by Caddy with a wildcard TLS
                        certificate — no extra setup required.
                    </p>
                </details>
            </div>
        </section>

    </article>
</div>

